[[File:Felice Beato (British, born Italy - George Campbell, Esquire, Bengal Civil Service) - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|Portrait]]
[[File:George_Campbell.jpg|thumb|Portrait]]

'''Sir George Campbell''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100|KCSI|}} (1824 – 18 February 1892) was a Scottish [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician and Indian administrator.

Campbell was born in 1824, the eldest son of Sir George Campbell, of Edenwood, whose brother became the [[John Campbell, 1st Baron Campbell|1st Baron Campbell]]. He was educated at [[Hamilton Academy]]<ref>Scottish Secondary Teachers' Association Magazine, February 1950, feature on Hamilton Academy in the article series 'Famous Scottish Schools'</ref> and embarked for India.
[[File:George Campbell, Vanity Fair, 1878-09-21.jpg|thumb|upright|left|"Indian authority". Caricature by [[Leslie Ward|Spy]] published in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine 1868-1914)|Vanity Fair]] in 1878.]]
From 1871 to 1874 he was Lieutenant-Governor of [[Bengal]]. During his tenure the [[Pabna District#History|Pabna Disturbances]] occurred. With his proclamation on 4 July 1873 during the [[Pabna Peasant Uprisings]], guaranteeing government support of peasants against excessive [[zamindar]] demands he ensured that the prostest remained peaceful, at the same time antagonising the landlords and his namesake [[George Campbell, 8th Duke of Argyll]] at that time Secretary of State for India.

He was [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Kirkcaldy Burghs (UK Parliament constituency)|Kirkcaldy Burghs]] from 1875 to 1892.

Campbell married, in 1853, Laetitia Maria Vibart, daughter of John Gowan Vibart, of the Bengal civil service, and left several children.
Lady Campbell died in London 21 October 1901, aged 68.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Obituary - Lady Campbell|day_of_week=Wednesday |date=23 October 1901 |page_number=7 |issue=36593| }}</ref> Their eldest son, Major George Campbell (ca. 1861-1902), died while serving with the [[King's Regiment (Liverpool)|8th King's Regiment]] in the [[Second Boer War]] in [[South Africa]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Deaths|day_of_week=Monday |date=10 March 1902 |page_number=1 |issue=36711| }}</ref>

