'''Marieme Jamme''' is a [[Senegal|Senegalese]] businesswoman. In 2017, Jamme was listed as one of [[100 Women (BBC)|BBC's 100 Women.]] <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-41380265|title=BBC 100 Women: Who is on the list?|date=2017-11-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> 

Jamme was honoured as a Young Global Leader by the [[World Economic Forum]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/people/marieme-jamme/|title=Authors|website=World Economic Forum}}</ref> for her activism work in empowering and investing in young girls and women in Africa, Middle East, and Asia through creative learning, entrepreneurship, science, technology, engineering, art, mathematics, and design (STEAMD). She has recently collaborated with a group of African leaders<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africagathering.org/press-release-african-data-platform-launched-to-challenge-global-development-community-for-accuracy-of-data-the-african-continent-deserves-better-and-more-accurate-data/|title=Press Release: African Data platform launched to challenge global development community for accuracy of Data: "The African continent deserves better and more accurate data"|publisher=}}</ref> to create Accur8Africa,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://accur8africa.com/|title=Accur8Africa – Africa Deserves Accurate Data|date=10 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> a new platform aiming at enabling governments, businesses, entrepreneurs, and the civil society in Africa at measuring the success of the [[Sustainable Development Goals]] by 2030 with Accurate Data. Jamme’s latest venture includes the launch of [[IAMTHECODE]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamthecode.org|title=iamtheCODE - iamtheCODE|website=iamtheCODE}}</ref> a new movement aiming at mobilising governments, businesses and investors to support girls and young women in STEAMD (Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts, Mathematics, and Design).

Jamme is also a regular international speaker,<ref>http://www.tedxamsterdamwomen.nl/meet-our-speakers-marieme-jamme-i-am-the-code/</ref> a tech entrepreneur and the co-founder of Africa Gathering, a global platform that brings together entrepreneurs and experts to exchange ideas about Africa's development. These are efforts to keep the African narrative relevant and positive.<ref>{{cite news|last=Curnow|first=Robyn|title=Marieme Jamme: Shaping Africa's tech revolution|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/07/24/world/marieme-jamme-africa-technology/|accessdate=14 October 2013|newspaper=CNN|date=24 July 2012}}</ref> She wrote in 2012 that "we are witnessing great progress in the continent and this needs to be highlighted.".<ref>{{cite news|last=Jamme|first=Mariéme|title='Change is imminent': African CEOs look to bright future|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/11/23/opinion/marieme-jamme-africa-ceo-forum/|accessdate=15 October 2013|newspaper=CNN}}</ref>

She is currently the CEO of SpotOne Global Solutions as well as the founder of iConscience.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Guardian Profile on Marieme Jamme|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/marieme-jamme}}</ref>  She was referred to as being 'at the forefront of the technology revolution that is slowly transforming Africa' by CNN.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marieme Jamme: Shaping Africa's tech revolution|last=Curnow|first=Robyn|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/07/24/world/marieme-jamme-africa-technology/index.html|newspaper=CNN}}</ref> She is also well-known for helping to organise the annual [[Apps4Africa]] competition.<ref>{{cite web|title=Apps4Africa: Using Crowdsourced Mobile Apps to Tackle Climate Change|url=http://rising.globalvoicesonline.org/blog/2012/03/25/apps4africa-using-crowdsourced-mobile-apps-to-tackle-climate-change/|publisher=Global Voices}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jamme|first=Marieme|title=Why tech innovators are Africa's future|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/02/22/opinion/apps4africa-marieme-jamme/index.html|accessdate=15 October 2013|newspaper=CNN}}</ref> Jamme also mentors founders and managers at some of Africa's technology and innovation hubs,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?url=http://www.gsma.com/mobilefordevelopment/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Tech-Hubs-in-Africa_Infographic.pdf|title=Tech-Hubs-in-Africa_Infographic.pdf|website=docs.google.com}}</ref> and is the co-founder of [[HiveColab]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Graham|first=Fiona|title=The workplaces building Africa's business future|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-19702011|accessdate=15 October 2013|newspaper=BBC.co.uk}}</ref>

== Early Life ==
Jamme grew up in rural Senegal, from an oligarch mother who gave her away at an early-age and was later raised in various foster houses including in an orphanage and then trafficked as a young prostitute to Paris. She experienced considerable hardship during her childhood and did not have a formative education until the age of 16 years old, when she taught herself how to read and write.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.biznespreneur.com/apply-tony-elumelu-100m-entrepreneurship-program-meet-strong-memeber-selection-committee/|title=Did You apply for Tony Elumelu $100M Entrepreneurship Program? Meet a strong member of the Selection Committee - Biznespreneur|last=Tomiwa|date=2017-03-27|work=Biznespreneur|access-date=2017-03-27|language=en-US}}</ref>

