{{Burmese name|Maung}} {{Infobox person | name = Maung Weik | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth-date and age|1973}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date†|birth date†}} --> | death_place = | nationality = Burmese | other_names = | occupation = | years_active = | known_for = Founder of Maung Weik & Family Company | notable_works = | alma_mater = | parents = | relatives = }}
'''Maung Weik''' ({{lang-my|မောင်ဝိတ်}}; born 1973<ref name="ml">{{cite news|url=http://www2.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=13256|title=Maung Weik Charged with Trafficking Drugs|last=Min Lwin|date=10 July 2008|work=The Irrawaddy|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>) is a former Burmese businessman and founder of the Maung Weik and Family Company, which had a presence in the development, real estate, trading, and construction sectors.<ref name="ml"/><ref name="az">{{cite news|url=http://www2.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=5010&page=9|title=Tycoon Turf|last=Aung Zaw|date=September 2005|work=The Irrawaddy|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> He was previously married to Yin Min Thee,<ref name="ml-2">{{cite news|url=http://www2.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=14699|title=Drug-Dealing Junta Crony Gets 15 Years|last=Min Lwin|date=26 November 2008|work=The Irrawaddy|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> the niece of [[Myint Swe (general)|Myint Swe]], the Chief Minister of [[Yangon Region]].<ref name="az"/> Maung Weik was a close associate of [[Khin Nyunt]], a former prime minister and military general. He reportedly catered to wealthy young people, notably the sons of the generals. According to the semi-official Myanmar Times, he has engaged in drug trafficking from Malaysia to Burma since 2003.<ref name="miz">{{cite news|url=http://archive-2.mizzima.com/news/inside-burma/690-maung-weik-still-under-detention-.html|title=Maung Weik still under detention|date=19 June 2008|work=Mizzima|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>
On 10 July 2008, he was charged with drug abuse and trafficking by the [[Lanmadaw Township]] police station, accused of importing [[MDMA|ecstasy]], methamphetamines, and [[ketamine]], and trafficking them to the children of Burmese military generals and actors.<ref name="ml"/><ref name="miz"/> In November 2008, he was sentenced by the Lanmadaw Township Court, to 15 years imprisonment on drug trafficking charges.<ref name="ml"/> He reportedly used drugs with Aung Ye Zaw Myint, the son of Ye Myint, a former chief of the Bureau of Special Operations.<ref name="ml-2"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive-2.mizzima.com/news/inside-burma/750-drug-investigation-heavy-punishment-likely-for-maung-weik.html|title=Drug investigation, heavy punishment likely for Maung Weik|date=3 July 2008|work=Mizzima|accessdate=29 October 2012}}</ref> Maung Weik was released from Pathein Prison on 3 January 2014.<ref name="sm">{{cite news|title=မြန်မာနိုင်ငံတွင် ကြီးနိုင်ငယ်ညှဉ်း နှိပ်စက်ခြင်း ကင်းဝေးပါစေ ဟု မောင်ဝိတ် ဆုတောင်း|last=Soe Moe|work=Yangon Media Group|language=Burmese|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>
